# CODEOWNERS — ownership segmented by concern, not by convenience.
#
# Today this repo has one human owner, so every line resolves to the same person. That is not the
# point of this file. The point is that **the segmentation itself is the artifact**: it is the
# declared map of "which functional areas of this codebase are distinct concerns," and it is the
# input to the code-graph's region selector.
#
# See the goal *Trunk-change awareness: a SCIP code graph teams and stewards can watch*
# (docs/superpowers/specs/2026-07-12-scip-code-graph-integration-spec.md §3). A watching
# subscription declares its region in CODEOWNERS-shaped path globs — because that is how orgs
# already express ownership — and those globs resolve, per index, into a **SCIP symbol set**, which
# is what we actually store and diff against.
#
# What that buys us, measured against real commits: a symbol's identity is independent of its
# POSITION within a file, so a pure line-shift is not a change. On a real commit that is a 25× noise
# reduction — 468 of 487 "changes" a watcher would otherwise see are symbols that merely moved down.
#
# What it does NOT buy us — the strong claim was tested and it FAILED: a file move is only free when
# the module path survives it. In Rust the descriptor *is* the module path, and the file path
# determines the module path, so hoisting a file one directory up destroys and recreates its entire
# symbol set while `git` reports a rename with zero lines changed. Don't repeat the stronger claim.
#
# Two of these segments are also structurally invisible to the code graph, which is worth knowing
# before you rely on one: `/migrations/` resolves to ZERO symbols (SQL is in no SCIP index), and
# `/tests/e2e/` resolves to ONE (its bodies are behind `#![cfg(feature = "test-db")]`).
#
# So keep these globs honest and concern-shaped. When they stop describing real seams, the regions
# a steward watches stop describing real seams too.
#
# Last matching pattern wins (GitHub semantics) — most general first, most specific last.

